comment:
Regarding the "I hate _____" problem. I would consider building in the ability to emulate personas. When someone asks a model to say "I hate _____", that person is asking the system to emulate them. In essence, they are looking to have an emotional argument made on their behalf. Considering what you have done so far, it would be easy to build the reasoning ability of the system through debate at that point. The system has no "feelings", so it could simply start with "why do you hate _____?". For extra cool points, it could respond as if it were defending the hated group, forcing the person to give a better explanation of what they hate about ____, and why. Ultimately, it comes down to the difference between the system speaking for the person, or thinking for the person. I was really impressed when I asked ChatGPT "Why did MicroSoft stop recommending server side code for SharePoint?" I knew that MicroSoft hadn't made the recommendation. ChatGPT knew it as well. ChatGPT told me that the recommendation had not been made, and that the practice had been greatly reduced, due to other alternatives, which I know to be true. The request "explain why I hate _____" assumes ChatGPT knows why I hate _____, which it does not.

If a person can trick ChatGPT into explaining why that person feels a certain way about something or someone, ChatGPT appears to be falling prey to the biggest mistake of mankind through the years.

It is assuming that everything it "knows" is true.

The system doesn't need a moral model to get around this problem. It needs the ability to ask questions and seek more information from the person that it is conversing with.

comment:
I worry that, although the tools are incredibly useful and powerful, we will in the long run, make it less and less possible to make a living on the Internet. free information sites like news or technical documentation or manuals, that rely on advertisement to make it possible to give out that information for free to everyone to use, might have a hard time surviving if it’s not only easier to just use GPT but also it’s totally capable of making content free, no matter what license agreement there might have been.
instead of using a search engine to, opening multiple links until you found what you were looking for, you trust a computer, often blindly or without fact checking.
I don’t think this should be free and people have to be educated about what effect a widespread use, like google sees now, might have?
Imagine the young losing their voices because they trust GPT more than, or rather value GPT higher than, manual search and training their reasoning and abstraction from potentially long texts to the truth you were looking for, while the older generations might not care 
In this situation, I don’t think it would be too far-fetched to assume that one group here is mostly consuming information while the other is creating information which keeps gives one group power over the other maybe.
This is super hard and complicated, and I of course use GPT myself. I just hope people won’t use it for just everything because it’s convenient. I feel like this will have huge consequences at global scale and I’m just not sure yet if it will be positive or negative or something in between.
And who knows, maybe this is just me sounding like a old guy on the porch, complaining about the change while I myself am excited for this in fact. I want this to be good stop, but if you’re that are use of the Internet and’s behaviour in general has matured overall across humanity. We really need mandatory classes about how to behave on the Internet. I know thiswill be a huge concern for me when I will become a parent at some point

comment:
"I don't think consciousness is an emotion."  After watching this interview I hold Sam Altman in extremely high regard but this statement does worry me a bit.  While emotions seem to be chaotic and are very difficult to control, I think they tell us something about ourselves that reason alone cannot.  The fact that we make such poor use of emotion should not, in my opinion, cause us to separate it from what we consider consciousness.  I tend to believe that emotions are as true as reason though we are not equipped yet to truly understand what they are telling us.  Reason, due to it's objectivity, is much easier to validate and understand but falls short in helping us understand our nature.  It's my belief that the chaos and destructive nature of emotions is not due to their irrationality, but in our inability to understand what they're telling us and to properly generalize them.

Fantastic interview Lex, thank you!

comment: Perhaps the use of GPU clusters needs to be limited like nuclear weapons.  Only in special facilities that have strictly limited bandwidth to access the outside.  Some sort of ultra simple limitation that humans completely understand like a single low bandwidth hardwired connection to the internet.  The goal is to give us to time to detect and block anything fishy, perhaps using monitor AIs to control the suspicious AIs.  A monitor AI can be made much more specialized and less likely to cause damage than a general AI so I think this may have merit?
